  "prompt": "How do I turn off screen overlay in Android?",
  "response": "Screen overlay is a feature on Android that allows certain apps to display content over other apps (e.g., chat heads, screen filters, or permission dialogs). However, it can sometimes interfere with app functionality, especially when trying to grant permissions. Here's how to turn off screen overlay on Android:\n\n### Steps to Turn Off Screen Overlay:\n1. **Go to Settings**:\n   - Open the **Settings** app on your Android device.\n\n2. **Access Apps & Notifications**:\n   - Navigate to **Apps & Notifications** (or just **Apps** on some devices).\n\n3. **Open App Permissions**:\n   - Tap **App permissions** or **Special app access** (depending on your device).\n\n4. **Select \"Display over other apps\"**:\n   - Find and tap on **Display over other apps** or **Draw over other apps**.\n\n5. **Identify the App(s) with Overlay Permission**:\n   - You\u2019ll see a list of apps that have permission to display over other apps.\n\n6. **Disable Overlay for Specific Apps**:\n   - Tap on the app(s) causing the issue and toggle off the **Allow display over other apps** option.\n\n### Troubleshooting:\n- If you\u2019re unable to disable the overlay because it blocks the permission dialog:\n  - Temporarily disable overlay permissions for all apps to resolve the issue.\n  - Restart your device and try again.\n\n### Notes:\n- Some apps, like Facebook Messenger (chat heads), require this permission to function properly. Turning it off may affect their behavior.\n- On newer Android versions, the exact steps may vary slightly depending on the device manufacturer or Android version.\n\nLet me know if you need further assistance!",
